@FullyTested
public final class FixedSizeListIterator<TValue>
extends ForwardingListIterator<TValue>

This class is a simple extension of ForwardingListIterator, where methods add(Object) and remove() are disabled -- always throw UnsupportedOperationException.

The class constructor is private. Instead, use static method of(ListIterator).

This class is final to disable modify-by-inheritance.

Why is this class not called ImmutableListIterator? Read more here: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/8892350/immutable-vs-unmodifiable-collection

Author:
Kevin Connor ARPE (kevinarpe@gmail.com)
See Also:

of

public static <TValue> FixedSizeListIterator<TValue> of(ListIterator<TValue> iter)
Returns an unmodifiable view of an underlying ListIterator. If the input is an instance of FixedSizeListIterator, this method avoids wrapping the iterator again -- the input value is returned untouched.

Parameters:
iter - list iterator to create an unmodifable view
Returns:
an unmodifiable view of underlying list iterator
